			Story 3 — Bromir’s Achievements and Daily Trials in Sunveil Market Town

	Bromir Ironfist stands at his forge as the sun climbs high over Sunveil Market Town, the heat of the furnaces reflecting in his determined eyes. He often recounts this part of his life with a mix of pride, exhaustion, and faint exasperation.

*"I came to this town with hammer and anvil in hand, ready to shape steel and craft wonders. And craft I have. Day after day, I have forged weapons, armors, shields, and tools of every kind. Every strike of my hammer carries knowledge earned in Aarong Forest and the Ancient City of Sankis. Every piece I craft is a testament to centuries of dwarven skill, refined and perfected through sweat and effort. Yet… the work is never done."*

	He chuckles dryly, gesturing to the cluttered workshop around him, the piles of finished goods, and the racks of untested armor.

*"I have two apprentices, eager but foolish at times. They scurry about, spilling powders, dropping hammers, misaligning rivets, and yet I continue to teach them. Every mistake is a lesson, every blunder an opportunity for growth — though I must admit, patience wears thin when they repeatedly fail to grasp the basics. Still, I do not abandon them; I cannot. Their hands may falter now, but one day they may carry on the work that I will leave behind. That, I tell myself, is enough."*

	He wipes his brow, dusting soot from his arms, eyes scanning the bustling town.

*"The townsfolk may not realize it, but my work here is not just about forging items for hunters or assisting those ascending the Tomb of Great Crusaders. It is about leaving a mark — about creating objects of quality, of durability, of precision. Each sword balanced to perfection, each shield tempered to withstand blows that would shatter ordinary metal, each armor piece designed to protect and inspire confidence. This is my legacy."*

	Bromir’s gaze softens as he glances at the anvil, then the apprentices fumbling nearby.

*"I am proud of what I have built here — not just the items, but the system, the organization, the knowledge passed on. But pride does not mean ease. Teaching, managing, crafting, and supervising a workshop of this size is an endless challenge. And yet, it is worth it. For when a blade leaves my forge, when a shield withstands the fiercest strike, when my apprentices finally understand what true craftsmanship means… I feel the weight of all those years, all those battles, all those lessons, and I know that my work matters."*

	He picks up a freshly forged sword, turning it in the light.

*"Sunveil Market Town may be small compared to Sankis, but it is alive, vibrant, and full of potential. And so, I hammer, I teach, I endure, and I strive for perfection, one strike at a time. Until my apprentices can truly hold the forge, I remain — Bromir Ironfist, master of steel, teacher of craft, and witness to the daily trials that make this town stronger."*

